odes\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Madam Secretary (TV series)|Madam Secretary]]''\n|June O'Callaghan\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Nancy Drew and the Hidden Staircase (2019 film)|Nancy Drew and the Hidden Staircase]]''\n|Flora\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]''\n|Jean\n|5 episodes\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Brockmire]]''\n|Lorraine\n|1 episode\n|}\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n=== Stage ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n|-\n|1962\n|''[[A Family Affair (musical)|A Family Affair]]''\n|-\n|1963\n|''The Riot Act\n|-\n|1964-1965\n|''Wet Paint''\n|-\n|1966\n|''[[It's a Bird...It's a Plane...It's Superman]]''\n|-\n|1966\n|''[[The Mad Show]]''\n|-\n|1967\n|''[[On a Clear Day You Can See Forever]]\n|-\n|1967\n|''Something Different''\n|-\n|1967\n|''[[Little Murders]]''\n|-\n|1969\n|''Cop-Out''\n|-\n|1969-1970\n|''[[Last of the Red Hot Lovers]]''\n|-\n|1970\n|''[[Paul Sills]]' Story Theater''\n|-\n|1973\n|''The Enemy is Dead''\n|-\n|1974\n|''[[Rich and Famous (play)|Rich and Famous]]''\n|-\n|1986-1987\n|''[[Broadway Bound]]''\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Gypsy (musical)|Gypsy]]''\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[The Sisters Rosensweig]]''\n|-\n|1995\n|''Death Defying Acts''\n|-\n|1996\n|''Cakewalk''\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[The Diary of Anne Frank (play)|The Diary of Anne Frank]]''\n|-\n|2000-2001\n|''[[The Tale of the Allergist's Wife]]''\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Hollywood Arms]]''\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Finishing the Picture]]''\n|-\n|2008\n|''The New Century''\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Follies]]''\n|-\n|2011-2012\n|''[[The Lyons]]''\n|-\n|2014\n|''Too Much Sun''\n|-\n|2016\n|''Our Mother's Brief Affair''\n|}\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Linda Lavin}}\n* {{IMDb name|492089}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|1942}}\n* [http://www.alicehyatt.com/cast/lavin/linda.html Linda Lavin biography, as \"Alice\" cast member]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Awards for Linda Lavin\n|list=\n{{DramaDesk PlayActress}}\n{{DramaDesk PlayFeaturedActress}}\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Actress TV Comedy}}\n{{TonyAward PlayLeadActress}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lavin, Linda}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Actress Golden Globe (television) winners]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary alumni]]\n[[Category:Drama Desk Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Portland, Maine]]\n[[Category:Actors from Wilmington, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Portland, Maine]]\n[[Category:Waynflete School alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Linda Lavin\n| image =Linda Lavin 2014.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption =Lavin in 2014\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1937|10|15|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Portland, Maine]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actress, singer\n| alma_mater= [[College of William & Mary]]\n| residence = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| years_active = 1967\u2013present\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Ron Leibman]]|1969|1980|end=divorced}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Kip Niven (actor)|Kip Niven]]|1982|1992|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|Steve Bakunas<br>|2005}}\n}}\n\n'''Linda Lavin''' (born October 15, 1937) is an American actress and singer. She is known for playing the title character in the [[situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Alice (TV series)|Alice]]'' and for her stage performances, both on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] and [[Off-Broadway]].\n\nAfter acting as a child, Lavin joined the [[Compass Players]] in the late 1950s. She began acting on Broadway in the 1960s, earning notice in ''[[It's a Bird...It's a Plane...It's Superman]]'' in 1966 and receiving her first [[Tony Award]] nomination in ''[[Last of the Red Hot Lovers]]'' in 1970. She moved to [[Hollywood]] in 1973 and began to work in television, making recurring appearances on the sitcom ''[[Barney Miller]]'' before getting the title role in hit comedy ''[[Alice (TV series)|Alice]]'', which ran from 1976 to 1985. She appeared in many [[telefilm]]s and later in other TV work. She has also had roles in several feature films.\n\nIn 1987, she returned to Broadway, starring in ''[[Broadway Bound]]'' (winning a [[Tony Award]]), ''[[Gypsy (musical)|Gypsy]]'' (1990), ''[[The Sisters Rosensweig]]'' (1993), ''[[The Diary of Anne Frank (play)|The Diary of Anne Frank]]'' (1997\u20131998) and ''[[The Tale of the Allergist's Wife]]'' (2000\u20132001), among others. In 2010, she appeared as Ruth Steiner in ''[[Collected Stories (play)|Collected Stories]]'', garnering her fifth Tony nomination. She starred in [[NBC]]'s short-lived [[sitcom]], ''[[Sean Saves the World]]'' as Lorna and the [[CBS]] sitcom ''[[9JKL]]''.\n\n== Early life and career ==\nLavin was born in [[Portland, Maine|Portland]], [[Maine]], the daughter of David Joseph Lavin, a businessman, and Lucille (''n\u00e9e'' Potter), an opera singer.<ref name=filmrefbio>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/0/Linda-Lavin.html \"Linda Lavin Biography\"]. FilmReference.com, accessed October 15, 2010</ref> The Lavin family were active members of the local area [[Jewish]] community.<ref name=LindaLavin>[http://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/lavin-linda \"Jewish Woman's Archive \u2013 Linda Lavin\"]. JWA.org, accessed July 11, 2014.</ref> Both sets of grandparents, Simon and Jessie Lavin and Harry and Esther Potter, emigrated from Russia.<ref>''1910 United States Federal Census''</ref> Her family was musically talented, and Lavin has been onstage since the age of five. She studied acting at [[HB Studio]]<ref>[https://hbstudio.org/about-hb-studio/alumni/ HB Studio Alumni]</ref> in New York City. She attended [[Waynflete School]] before enrolling in the [[College of William & Mary]]. While at William and Mary, she performed with the William and Mary Theater in many productions directed by long-time Professor Howard Scammon. In the summer of 1958, she played one of the leads in ''[[The Common Glory]]'', an outdoor drama written by Pulitzer-Prize winning playwright [[Paul Green (playwright)|Paul Green]] and staged at an amphitheater on campus. Upon her graduation from William and Mary,<ref name=jewish>Embry, Ingerline Voosen.[http://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/lavin-linda \"Linda Lavin biography\"] Jewish Women's Archive, retrieved October 15, 2010</ref> she had already received her [[Actors' Equity Association]] card. She was a member of the [[Compass Players]] in the late 1950s.<ref>Yearwood, Pauline Dubkin. [http://www.chicagojewishnews.com/story.htm?sid=3&id=253486 \"In the beginning: As Second City marks 50 years, a look at its Jewish founders and Jewish stars\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615014558/http://www.chicagojewishnews.com/story.htm?sid=3&id=253486 |date=2011-06-15 }}. Chicagojewishnews.com, December 11, 2009</ref> By the early 1960s, Lavin had appeared in several [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] shows and appeared on the 1966 [[cast recording]]s of ''[[The Mad Show]]'' performing Stephen Sondheim's \"[[The Boy From...]]\". From ''[[It's a Bird...It's a Plane...It's Superman]]'', one of her numbers, \"[[You've Got Possibilities]]\", was the album's best-received song and was called \"The one memorable song...flirty, syncopated\" by the ''Dallas Observer''.<ref>Liner, Elaine. [http://www.dallasobserver.com/2010-07-01/culture/in-the-dallas-theater-center-s-super-fun-superman-musical-you-don-t-need-x-ray-vision-to-see-deeper-themes/ Superman Musical, You Don't Need X-Ray Vision To See Deeper Themes\"]. ''Dallas Observer'', July 1, 2010</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Television and film ===\nIn 1967, Lavin made an appearance as Gloria Thorpe in a television version of the [[Musical film|musical]] ''[[Damn Yankees]]'' with [[Phil Silvers]].<ref>Hischak, Thomas S.[https://books.google.com/books?id=XbBz3C4Gr0EC&pg=PA183&lpg=PA183&dq=%22Damn+Yankees%22+%22Linda+Lavin%22&source=bl&ots=9lLrjuXt_w&sig=wPGxO-vlkvNVK14CWyX5VLOqrhg&hl=en#v=onepage&q=%22Damn%20Yankees%22%20%22Linda%20Lavin%22&f=false \"'Damn Yankees' Casts\"] ''The Oxford Companion to the American Musical'', Oxford University Press US, 2008, {{ISBN|0-19-533533-3}}, p. 183</ref> In 1969, Lavin married actor [[Ron Leibman]],<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/31/Ron-Leibman.html Leibman biography] filmreference.com, retrieved October 15, 2010</ref> and by 1973, the couple had arrived in Hollywood, California. After various guest appearances on episodic television series such as ''[[The Nurses (CBS TV series)|The Nurses]]'', ''[[Rhoda]]'', ''[[Harry O]]'' and ''[[Kaz (TV series)|Kaz]]'',<ref name=filmrefbio/> Lavin landed a recurring role as Detective Janice Wentworth on ''[[Barney Miller]]'' during the first and second seasons (1975\u20131976).<ref>[http://classicsitcoms.com/shows/barney1.html \"'Barney Miller', see March 13, 1975\"] classicsitcoms.com, accessed June 20, 2011</ref>\n\nShe left ''Barney Miller'' to star in the lead role in ''[[Alice (TV series)|Alice]]''. The show was a popular hit for [[CBS]] and ran from 1976 to 1985.<ref name=filmrefbio/> The series was based on the [[Martin Scorsese]]-directed [[Ellen Burstyn]] film ''[[Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore]]''.<ref>{{IMDb title|id=0073955|title=Alice}}</ref> Lavin portrayed Alice Hyatt, a waitress and singer, the character that Burstyn had played. Lavin performed the series' theme song, \"There's a New Girl in Town,\" which was written by [[David Shire]] and [[Alan and Marilyn Bergman]] and was updated for each of the first six seasons. During the series' nine-season run, Lavin earned two [[Golden Globe Award]]s and a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination,<ref>Terrece, Vincent. [https://books.google.com/books?id=AKlgjBCPPnsC&pg=PA10&dq=Alice++%22Linda+Lavin%22+television&hl=en#v=onepage&q=Alice%20%20%22Linda%20Lavin%22%20television&f=false \"'Alice' listing\"]. ''Encyclopedia of Television Series, Pilots and Specials: 1974\u20131984'' (1985), VNR AG, {{ISBN|0-918432-61-8}}, pp. 9\u201310</ref> and gained experience directing, especially during the later seasons. Lavin also played a dual role in ''Alice'', as Debbie Walden, the wizened and former landlady of the character Vera Louise Gorman-Novak.<ref name=block>[http://www.blockbuster.com/browse/catalog/personDetails/36025 \"Linda Lavin Movies, see 'Alice'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728053122/http://www.blockbuster.com/browse/catalog/personDetails/36025 |date=2011-07-28 }} blockbuster.com, accessed June 20, 2011</ref> Lavin also made numerous television appearances outside of ''Alice'', including hosting her own holiday special for [[CBS]], ''Linda in Wonderland'' (1980).<ref name=filmrefbio/> She acted in two sitcoms, ''[[Room for Two (TV series)|Room for Two]]'' (1992\u201393)<ref name=block/> and 1998's ''[[Conrad Bloom]]''.<ref>[http://www.tvguide.com/detail/tv-show.aspx?tvobjectid=100095&more=ucepisodelist&episodeid=941894 \"'Conrad Bloom' Episodes\"] tvguide.com, accessed June 20, 2011</ref> In ''Room for Two'', she played a mother who moved in with her daughter, played by [[Patricia Heaton]], who has a show on a local television station. The daughter gives Lavin's character her own segment, called Just a Thought, at the end of her program.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bobbin|first=Jay|title=Linda Lavin stars in \"Room for Two\"|newspaper=Savannah News -Press|date=August 30 \u2013 September 5, 1992}}</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0492089/?ref_=nv_sr_3 IMdB]</ref>\n\nAfter working in theater for many years, Lavin was cast in the NBC television [[sitcom]] ''[[Sean Saves the World]]'' (2013\u201314) playing [[Sean Hayes (actor)|Sean Hayes]]' pushy, meddling mother Lorna. The ''Los Angeles Times'' interviewer noted: \"A highlight of the show is the wonderful chemistry between Lavin and Hayes, who exchange repartee and quips with breezy ease. And the cast seems smitten with her.\"<ref>King, Susan. [http://articles.latimes.com/2013/dec/30/entertainment/la-et-st-linda-lavin-classic-hollywood-20131230 \"Linda Lavin recalls 'Alice'\"] ''Los Angeles Times'', December 30, 2013</ref>\n\nShe made numerous television guest appearances, including roles on ''[[The Muppet Show]]'' (1979), ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'', ''[[The O.C.]]'', ''[[Touched by an Angel]]'' (1999)<ref name=filmrefbio/> and [[HBO]]'s ''[[The Sopranos]]'' (2002).\n\nShe also appeared in many [[telefilm]]s between 1967 and 1998, including: ''Damn Yankees!'', ''Sadbird'', ''[[The Morning After (1974 film)|The Morning After]]'', ''Jerry'', ''Like Mom, Like Me'', ''The $5.20 an Hour Dream'', ''Another Woman's Child'', ''Maricela'', ''Lena: My 100 Children'', ''Whitewash'', ''A Dream is a Wish Your Heart Makes: The [[Annette Funicello]] Story'', ''Stolen Memories: Secrets from the Rose Garden'', ''For the Future: The Irvine Fertility Scandal'', ''The Ring'', and ''Best Friends for Life''.<ref name=\"filmrefbio\" /> Lavin produced and starred in ''A Matter of Life and Death'', the 1981 telefilm based on the work of nurse [[thanatologist]] [[Joy Ufema]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1917&dat=19801122&id=1AdHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZOkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2372,8809986&hl=en|title=In her own special|last=Scott|first=Vernon|date=November 22, 1980|website=news.google.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/0/Linda-Lavin.html|title=Linda Lavin Biography (1937\u2013)|website=www.filmreference.com|access-date=2016-09-19}}</ref> She directed the 1990 telefilm ''[[Flour Babies]]''.<ref name=block/><ref>{{IMDb title|id=0386467|title=Flour Babies}}</ref>\n\nLavin made her feature film debut in ''[[The Muppets Take Manhattan]]'' (1984).<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/152583%7C0/The-Muppets-Take-Manhattan.html \"'The Muppets Take Manhattan' Listing\"] tcm.com, accessed June 20, 2011</ref> Her other feature film appearances include ''[[See You in the Morning (film)|See You in the Morning]]'', starring [[Jeff Bridges]], and [[Alain Resnais]]'s ''[[I Want to Go Home (1989 film)|I Want to Go Home]]'', opposite [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]] (both 1989) and ''[[The Back-up Plan]]'' (2010).<ref name=pbsbio>[https://www.pbs.org/hollywoodpresents/collectedstories/roles/roles_lavin.html \"Linda Lavin Biography\"] pbs.org, accessed June 20, 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Lavin guest starred as a judge approached to stop an execution in the episode of ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' titled \"The Verdict in the Victims.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hill|first1=Selena|title='Bones' Season 10 Spoilers: 'The Good Wife' Actress Linda Lavin to Join Cast; T.J. Thyne and Michaela Conlin Tease Hodgins, Angela Relationshjip|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/37105/20150211/bones-season-10-spoilers-good-wife-actress-linda-lavin-join.htm|accessdate=April 10, 2018|publisher=Latin Post|date=February 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gleman|first1=Vlada|title=Bones: Linda Lavin to Help Booth and Brennan Save an Innocent Killer|url=http://tvline.com/2015/02/09/bones-season-10-cast-linda-lavin-judge/|accessdate=April 10, 2018|publisher=TV Line|date=February 9, 2015}}</ref> [[Emily Deschanel]] said \"Lavin was particularly fun to have on\" the show.<ref>{{cite news|title=5 things you need to know before Bones returns on March 26|url=https://www.globaltv.com/featuredarticles/latest/5-things-you-need-to-know-before-bones-returns-on-march-26/|accessdate=April 10, 2018|publisher=Global TV|date=March 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nLavin played Judy Roberts in the [[CBS]] sitcom ''[[9JKL]]'' (2017\u201318) alongside [[Mark Feuerstein]] and [[Elliott Gould]]. Lavin caught up with ''[[Portland Magazine]]'' in its Winterguide 2018 issue about her return to CBS stating, \"Like ''Alice'', ''9JKL'' deals with family relationships\u2013except it's a more sophisticated and edgier show. The people are more privileged and on a higher economic level than Alice. I love to go to work every day. I feel very grateful and fortunate for this role, the quality of work and good people at this stage of my life. Fun and creative are the operative words for me. I'm very committed to participating in projects where I can bring and exchange those qualities with like-minded people.\"<ref>Hrehovcik, Steve. [http://www.portlandmonthly.com/issues/winterguide2018/?page=62 \"Loving Linda Lavin\"] ''Portland Magazine'', Winterguide 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Lavin joined the cast of the Netflix comedy/horror ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]'', starring [[Drew Barrymore]] and [[Timothy Olyphant]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Foutch |first1=Haleigh |title='Santa Clarita Diet' Season 3's Delicious Delights Confirm It's the Best Horror Comedy on TV |url=http://collider.com/santa-clarita-diet-season-3-review/ |accessdate=March 30, 2019 |work=Collider |date=March 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Theater ===\nLavin began her career with [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] appearances in the musical ''[[A Family Affair (musical)|A Family Affair]]'' (1962)<ref>Ruhlmann, William. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-family-affair-original-cast-w132311 \"'A Family Affair' Review\"] allmusic.com, accessed April 8, 2012</ref> and plays such as ''The Riot Act'' (1963)<ref name=broadway>[http://www.ibdb.com/person.php?id=49068 \"Linda Lavin Broadway credits\"]. Internet Broadway Database, accessed February 16, 2012</ref> and [[Carl Reiner]]'s ''Something Different'' (1967).<ref>Barnes, Clive. \"Theater: 'Something Different' Opens: Carl Reiner Comedy Staged by Carl Reiner Claudia McNeil Plays a Mother for Hire The Cast\", ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 29, 1967, p. 52</ref> In his ''New York Times'' review of [[John Guare]]'s two one-act plays, ''Cop-Out'' (1969), [[Clive Barnes]] wrote: \"Miss Lavin...carries versatility almost to the point of paranoia, and camps up a storm.\"<ref>Barnes, Clive. \"Theater: Guare's Humorous 'Cop-Out': Ron Leibman and Linda Lavin Star at Cort\", ''The New York Times'', April 8, 1969, p. 42</ref>\n\nShe \"arrived at showbiz stardom with a featured role\" in the musical ''[[It's a Bird...It's a Plane...It's Superman]]'' (1966).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=MuECAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA97&dq=It's-a-Bird-It's-a-Plane-It's-Superman+%22Linda+Lavin%22&hl=en#v=onepage&q=It's-a-Bird-It's-a-Plane-It's-Superman%20%22Linda%20Lavin%22&f=false \"Nightlife\" listings]. ''New York Magazine'', April 1, 1996, p. 97</ref><ref>Henderson, Kathy. [http://www.broadway.com/shows/collected-stories/buzz/151805/collected-stories-star-linda-lavin-on-her-50-years-onstage-and-her-real-life-love-story/ \"Collected Stories Star Linda Lavin on Her 50 Years Onstage and Her Real-Life Love Story\"]. Broadway.com, May 3, 2010</ref> She received her first [[Tony Award]] nomination in 1970, for her role in the [[Neil Simon]] play, ''[[Last of the Red Hot Lovers]]'' (1969). Clive Barnes, in his review for ''The New York Times'', wrote: \"Linda Lavin, eyebrows, [sic] flaunting like telegraphed messages, mouth twitching and pouting, voice as dry as thunder and with a cough like electric static, is beautiful as Elaine, the sex cat feeling coolly kittenish and looking for a safe tin roof.\"<ref name=broadway/><ref>Barnes, Clive. \"Stage: 'Red Hot Lovers': Comedy by Neil Simon Opens at the O'Neill\", ''The New York Times'', December 29, 1969, p. 37</ref> Lavin's last Broadway credit before she moved to Hollywood was in ''[[Paul Sills' Story Theatre]]'' in 1971.<ref name=creditsbww>[http://broadwayworld.com/people/Linda_Lavin/ \"Linda Lavin Stage Performances\"]. Broadwayworld.com, accessed February 16, 2012</ref>\n\nIn her early years, Lavin also appeared in numerous [[Off-Broadway]] productions, including the revue ''Wet Paint'' (1965),<ref>Funke, Lewis. \"The Theater: 'Wet Paint' : Eager-to-Please Revue Opens at Renata\", ''The New York Times'', April 13, 1965, p. 33</ref> the musical ''[[The Mad Show]]'' (1966)<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=3935 Internet Off-Broadway database listing, \"'The Mad Show'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907072658/http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=3935 |date=2009-09-07 }}. Internet Off-Broadway Database, retrieved October 15, 2010</ref> and ''Little Murders'' (1969). Lavin won the [[Theatre World Award]] for ''Wet Paint''<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=4038 Internet Off-Broadway database listing, 'Wet Paint'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011183531/http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=4038 |date=2012-10-11 }} Internet Off-Broadway Database, retrieved October 15, 2010</ref> and a [[Drama Desk Award]] for ''Little Murders''.<ref>[http://www.dramadesk.com/1968_1969dd.html \"Drama Desk Awards, 1968\u20131969] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20080704130834/http://www.dramadesk.com/1968_1969dd.html |date=2008-07-04 }}. Dramadesk.com, retrieved October 15, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=2500 Internet Off-Broadway database listing, \"'Little Murders'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316115811/http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=2500 |date=2012-03-16 }}. Internet Off-Broadway Database, retrieved October 15, 2010</ref> In 1975, she appeared in the [[Shakespeare in the Park (New York City)]] production of ''[[The Comedy of Errors]]'' at the [[Delacorte Theater]].\n\nIn 1984, Lavin played the character of \"The Mother\" in Luigi Pirandello's ''Six Characters in Search of an Author'' in a production directed by Robert Brustein at the American Repertory Theatre in Cambridge, Massachusetts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americanrepertorytheater.org/shows-events/six-characters-in-search-of-an-author/|title=Six Characters in Search of an Author|website=A.R.T.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a decade away, appearing on television, Lavin returned to the Broadway stage in 1987, winning a [[Tony Award]] for Best Actress in a Play<ref>[http://www2.broadwayworld.com/tonyawardsyear.cfm?year=1987 \"1987 Tony Awards\"]. broadwayworld.com, accessed February 16, 2012</ref> and her second [[Drama Desk Award]] for her role as Kate in Simon's play ''[[Broadway Bound]]''. [[Frank Rich]], in his ''[[New York Times]]'' review, wrote: \"One only wishes that Ms. Lavin, whose touching performance is of the same high integrity as the writing, could stay in the role forever.\"<ref>Rich, Frank. [http://theater.nytimes.com/mem/theater/treview.html?res=9A0DE1D7113AF936A35751C1A960948260 \"Theater: Simon's 'Broadway Bound'\"], ''The New York Times'', December 5, 1986</ref> Theatre critic Charles McNulty wrote of her performance that it \"is widely considered one of the most memorable in contemporary Broadway history, winning not just awards but praise approaching the level of myth. The distinguished theater critic [[Gordon Rogoff]], extolling 'the power available only to an actor at the height of her own command of detail,' went so far as to describe Lavin's portrayal as 'one of those textbook lessons in great acting...' \"<ref>McNulty, Charles. [http://articles.latimes.com/2011/feb/20/entertainment/la-ca-linda-lavin-20110220 \"Linda Lavin is awash in good fortune\"]. ''Los Angeles Times'', February 20, 2011</ref>\n\nShe then starred on Broadway in ''[[Gypsy (musical)|Gypsy]]'' as Mama Rose Hovick, replacing [[Tyne Daly]] in July 1990.<ref>Rich, Frank.[https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/18/theater/review-theater-linda-lavin-takes-her-turn-as-mama-rose.html \"Review/Theater; Linda Lavin Takes Her Turn as Mama Rose\"]. ''The New York Times'', September 18, 1990</ref> [[June Havoc]] saw Lavin's performance in ''Gypsy'' and sent Lavin a photo of Havoc's mother, the real Rose Hovick, with a note of appreciation for Lavin's particular portrayal of the character.<ref>[http://www.aislesay.com/FTR-LAVIN.html \"Linda Lavin\"]. Aislesay.com</ref>\n\nSubsequent Broadway roles included ''[[The Sisters Rosensweig]]'', as a replacement Gorgeous Teitelbaum starting in September 1993<ref>Brantley, Ben. \"New Cast for 'Sisters Rosensweig'\", ''The New York Times'', September 24, 1993, p.C3</ref> and Mrs. Van Daan in ''[[The Diary of Anne Frank (play)|The Diary of Anne Frank]]'' (1997\u20131998), opposite [[Natalie Portman]], for which she garnered a Tony nomination as Featured Actress in a Play.<ref name=creditsbww/><ref>[http://www2.broadwayworld.com/tonyawardsyear.cfm?year=1998 \"1998 Tony Awards\"]. Broadwayworld.com, accessed February 16, 2012</ref> In 1995 she appeared in the Off-Broadway ''Death-Defying Acts'', which consists of three one-act plays; Lavin performed in the [[Elaine May]] (\"Hotline\") and [[Woody Allen]] plays (\"Central Park West\").<ref>Gerard, Jeremy.  [http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117909905?refcatid=31 \"'Death Defying Acts'\"]. ''Variety'', March 12, 1995</ref> She was nominated for a Drama Desk Award (Outstanding Actress \u2013 Play)<ref>[http://www.dramadesk.org/1994_1995dd.html \"Drama Desk, 1994\u201395\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} dramadesk.org, accessed April 8, 2012</ref> and won an [[Obie Award]] (Performance)<ref>[http://www.villagevoice.com/obies/index/1995/ \"Obies, 1995 Award Winners\"] villagevoice.com, accessed April 8, 2012</ref> and the [[Lucille Lortel Award]]. She also directed theater during this period.\n\nShe played Marjorie in ''[[The Tale of the Allergist's Wife]]'' (2000\u20132001), co-starring [[Tony Roberts (actor)|Tony Roberts]] and [[Michele Lee]], for which she was nominated for a Tony Award, Leading Actress in a Play, and Drama Desk Award,<ref>Jones, Kenneth. [https://archive.is/20120909001746/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/61427-Linda-Lavins-Fine-Whine-Runs-Dry-in-Bways-Tale-July-29 \"Linda Lavin's Fine Whine Runs Dry in Bway's Tale July 29\"]. Playbill.com, July 29, 2001</ref> and \"nanny\" for Helen (young [[Carol Burnett]], played by [[Sara Niemietz]] and [[Donna Lynne Champlin]]) in ''[[Hollywood Arms]]'' in Chicago and on Broadway in 2002.<ref>Murray, Matthew. [http://www.talkinbroadway.com/world/HollywoodArms.html Review]. talkinbroadway.com, October 31, 2002</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Lavin appeared as Ruth Steiner in a Broadway revival of the play ''[[Collected Stories (play)|Collected Stories]]'',<ref>Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/138569-Lavin-Paulson-Star-in-Collected-Stories-Making-Broadway-Bow-April-9 \"Lavin & Paulson Star in Collected Stories, Making Broadway Bow April 9\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504093359/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/138569-Lavin-Paulson-Star-in-Collected-Stories-Making-Broadway-Bow-April-9 |date=2010-05-04 }}. Playbill.com, April 9, 2010</ref> reprising her role for a [[PBS]] production of the play,<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/hollywoodpresents/collectedstories/roles/roles_lavin.html \"Collected Stories information\"] pbs.org, retrieved October 15, 2010</ref> and received a fifth Tony nomination for the role. She appeared in the new play by [[Jon Robin Baitz]], ''[[Other Desert Cities]]'', [[Off-Broadway]] at the Mitzi Newhouse Theater ([[Lincoln Center]]) beginning in previews in December 2010, closing February 27, 2011.<ref>[http://www.lct.org/showMain.htm?id=201 \" 'Desert Cities' Listing\"] Lincoln Center, accessed May 29, 2011</ref> Lavin was featured in the [[Kennedy Center]] (Washington, DC) production of the musical ''[[Follies]]'', from May 2011 to June 2011, as Hattie Walker.<ref name=playoct>Gans, Andrew.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/150498-Hats-Off-Here-They-Come-Those-Beautiful-Girls-Starry-Follies-Begins-Kennedy-Center-Run-May-7 \"Hats Off, Here They Come, Those Beautiful Girls\": Starry 'Follies' Begins Kennedy Center Run May 7\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110508214902/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/150498-Hats-Off-Here-They-Come-Those-Beautiful-Girls-Starry-Follies-Begins-Kennedy-Center-Run-May-7 |date=2011-05-08 }}. Playbill.com, May 7, 2011</ref>\n\nShe appeared in the premiere of the [[Nicky Silver]] play ''[[The Lyons]]'' at the Off-Broadway [[Vineyard Theatre]], beginning in September 2011, through November 11.<ref>Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/155352-Nicky-Silvers-Lyons-Led-by-Linda-Lavin-and-Dick-Latessa-Opens-in-NYC-Extension-to-Nov-11-Announced \"Nicky Silver's ''Lyons'', Led by Linda Lavin and Dick Latessa, Opens in NYC; Extension to Nov. 11 Announced\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226121220/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/155352-Nicky-Silvers-Lyons-Led-by-Linda-Lavin-and-Dick-Latessa-Opens-in-NYC-Extension-to-Nov-11-Announced |date=2012-02-26 }}. Playbill.com, October 11, 2011</ref> [[Ben Brantley]], ''The New York Times'' reviewer, commented: \"Watching Ms. Lavin, I found myself thinking of Nora from Ibsen's ''[[A Doll's House|Doll's House]]'' \u2013 well, a pursed-lipped, lemony-sour, older Nora in pseudo-Chanel, one who's never at a loss for what to say and when to say it. Rita may be a little behind schedule in discovering herself, but no one can fault the hair-trigger timing of the actress playing her or the surprising dimensions she finds within one-liners.\"<ref>Brantley, Ben. [http://theater.nytimes.com/2011/10/12/theater/reviews/the-lyons-by-nicky-silver-at-vineyard-theater-review.html \"Theater Review:The Curse of Kinship, but a Fear of Isolation\"]. ''The New York Times'', October 11, 2011</ref> She reprised her role in the Broadway production, which opened at the [[Cort Theatre]] on April 23, 2012 and closed on July 1, 2012.<ref>Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/161453-The-Lyons-Led-By-Linda-Lavin-and-Dick-Latessa-Set-Up-Their-Den-on-Broadway \"''The Lyons'', Led By Linda Lavin and Dick Latessa, Set Up Their Den on Broadway\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406125232/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/161453-The-Lyons-Led-By-Linda-Lavin-and-Dick-Latessa-Set-Up-Their-Den-on-Broadway |date=2012-04-06 }} Playbill.com, April 5, 2012</ref><ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/167592-Nicky-Silvers-The-Lyons-Ends-Its-Broadway-Roar-July-1 \"Nicky Silver's ''The Lyons'' Ends Its Broadway Roar July 1\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120703022933/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/167592-Nicky-Silvers-The-Lyons-Ends-Its-Broadway-Roar-July-1 |date=2012-07-03 }} Playbill.com, July 1, 2012</ref>\n\nLavin appeared in the new Nicky Silver play ''Too Much Sun'', which opened Off-Broadway at the Vineyard Theatre on May 18, 2014. Ben Brantley, in his review for ''The New York Times'' wrote: \"And it's an unconditional treat to witness an actress like Ms. Lavin tuned so precisely into the writer's wavelength that script and performance become a marriage of true minds.\"<ref>Brantley, Ben.[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/theater/nicky-silvers-too-much-sun-stars-linda-lavin.html?hpw&rref=theater&_r=1# \"Nicky Silver's ''Too Much Sun'' Stars Linda Lavin\"] ''The New York Times'', May 18, 2014</ref>\n\nLavin appeared in 2015/16 on Broadway at the [[Samuel J. Friedman Theatre]] in a [[Manhattan Theatre Club]] production of [[Richard Greenberg]]'s ''Our Mother's Brief Affair''.<ref>Clement, Olivia. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/our-mothers-brief-affair-with-linda-lavin-begins-previews-on-broadway-tonight-376583# \"'Our Mother's Brief Affair', with Linda Lavin, Begins Previews On Broadway Tonight\"], ''[[Playbill]]'', December 28, 2015</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Lavin appeared in [[New York City Opera]]'s production of Leonard Bernstein's ''[[Candide (operetta)|Candide]]'' at the Rose Theatre at [[Lincoln Center]] in the role of The Old Lady.<ref>[http://observer.com/2017/01/old-lady-linda-lavin-animates-nycos-stale-candide/ \"'Old Lady' Linda Lavin Animates NYCO's Stale ''Candide''\"] by [[James Jorden]], ''[[New York Observer]]'', January 9, 2017</ref>\n\n===Cabaret and recording===\nLavin has appeared in [[cabaret]] and concert performances.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [https://archive.is/20120913235850/http://www.playbill.com/celebritybuzz/article/98119-DIVA-TALK-Chatting-with-Tony-Award-Winner-Linda-Lavin-Plus-News-of-LuPone-and-McGovern/pg1 \"Diva Talk:Linda Lavin\"] playbill.com, February 24, 2006</ref> In 2005 she appeared at the Empire Plush Room in San Francisco, accompanied by Billy Stritch<ref>Gans, Andrew.[http://wwwm.playbill.com/news/article/94908-Linda-Lavin-Kicks-Off-Fall-Season-at-Plush-Room-Sept-6 Linda Lavin Kicks Off Fall Season at Plush Room Sept. 6\"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} playbill.com, September 6, 2005</ref> and her husband, Steve Bakunas. The ''talkinbroadway'' reviewer summed up her performance: \"Linda Lavin is funny, warm and full of personality.\"<ref>Connema, Richard.[http://www.talkinbroadway.com/regional/sanfran/s679.html \"Linda Lavin is the Life of the Party\"] talkinbroadway.com (regional), September 17, 2005</ref> In April 2006 she performed at [[Birdland (jazz club)|Birdland]] (New York) \"with her critically acclaimed cabaret act The Song Remembers When\", with [[Billy Stritch]].<ref>Gans, Andrew. [https://archive.is/20120910173628/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/97479-Clark-McArdle-Luker-Pedi-Lavin-Morton-and-More-Set-for-Birdlands-Spring-Season Clark, \"McArdle, Luker, Pedi, Lavin, Morton and More Set for Birdland's Spring Season\"] playbill.com, January 23, 2006</ref> She performed with the Wilmington Symphony ([[Wilmington, North Carolina]]) in March 2012.<ref>Staton, John.[http://www.starnewsonline.com/article/20120314/ENT/120319829 Broadway-bound Lavin's cabaret act full of 'Possibilities'\"] March 14, 2012</ref>\n\nHer recording, ''Possibilities'' was released by Ghostlight Records in 2012. Steven Suskin wrote: \"There is still that sweet, friendly sound of long ago (and 'sweet' and 'friendly' are not words you'd use to describe Lavin-the-actress).\"<ref>Suskin, Steven. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/158113-ON-THE-RECORD-Elf-Songs-From-a-Stage-Door-Canteen-Concert-Linda-Lavins-Possibilities \"On the Record. Elf, Songs From a Stage Door Canteen Concert, Linda Lavin's \"Possibilities\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419190549/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/158113-ON-THE-RECORD-Elf-Songs-From-a-Stage-Door-Canteen-Concert-Linda-Lavins-Possibilities |date=2012-04-19 }} playbill.com, January 1, 2012</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Lavin Follies.jpg|thumb|Lavin and husband Steve Bakunas at the Kennedy Center, June 19, 2011]]\nLavin has been married three times. Her first marriage to [[Ron Leibman]] ended in divorce in 1980. Her second marriage to [[Kip Niven]], whom she met on the set of ''Alice'', ended in a bitter divorce in 1992.<ref>Brozan, Nadine.[https://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/03/style/chronicle-471292.html \"Chronicle\"] ''The New York Times'', July 3, 1992</ref> While Lavin has no biological children, she is stepmother to the children of her second husband and plays an active role in their lives and that of her grandchildren, and is stepmother to those of her third and current husband, artist/musician Steve Bakunas, whom she married in 2005.<ref>Key, Lindsay.[http://www.wrightsvillebeachmagazine.com/article.asp?aid=599&iid=76 \"The Art of Love\"] ''Wrightsville Beach Magazine'', February 2010.</ref> The couple had resided in [[Wilmington, North Carolina]]<ref name=playoct/> where they were committed community members working together to rehabilitate impoverished neighborhoods including renovating many homes, donating a park to the city and creating a [[community theatre]], the Red Barn Studio. In 1997, Lavin founded The Linda Lavin Arts Foundation in Wilmington, \"to promote and foster the advancement of the performing and visual arts, with special emphasis on arts in education. Her foundation has created a theater program called Girl Friends, whose purpose is to raise the self-esteem of at-risk teenage girls of the inner city.\"<ref name=pbsbio/>\n\nBoth of her ex-husbands, the aforementioned Niven and Leibman, died in 2019 along with ''Alice'' co-stars [[Philip McKeon]] and [[Charles Levin (actor)|Charles Levin]].   \n\nIn Wilmington, she was a stage director. One of her directorial credits was a 1998 production of [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[As You Like It]]'', updated to a Brazilian jazz style. In both Wilmington and New York she teaches [[master class]]es in acting and singing.<ref name=pbsbio />\n\nIn September 2012 Lavin announced that she intended to sell her home in Wilmington and return to New York City.<ref>[http://www.starnewsonline.com/article/20120907/ENT/120909766/1177?Title=Linda-Lavin-relocating-to-New-York \"Linda Lavin\"] starnewsonline.com, September 7, 2012</ref> Lavin and Bakunas have lived in New York City since circa 2013\u20132014.<ref>Shaw, Dan.[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/realestate/linda-lavin-by-day-and-by-night.html# \"Linda Lavin, By Day and Night\"] ''The New York Times'', April 2014</ref> In July 2016, the Luxury Living website posted Lavin's Central Park South apartment for sale at $1.25 million.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nLavin was inducted into the [[American Theater Hall of Fame]] for 2010 in January 2011.<ref>Gans, Andrew and Peter, Thomas.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/146911-Theater-Hall-of-Fame-Ceremony-Honoring-Linda-Lavin-Brian-Dennehy-Michael-Blakemore-Presented-Jan-24 \"Theater Hall of Fame Ceremony, Honoring Linda Lavin, Brian Dennehy, Michael Blakemore, Presented Jan. 24\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222204659/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/146911-Theater-Hall-of-Fame-Ceremony-Honoring-Linda-Lavin-Brian-Dennehy-Michael-Blakemore-Presented-Jan-24 |date=2014-02-22 }} playbill.com, January 24, 2011</ref>\n\n'''Tony Awards'''\n*1970 Best Performance by a Featured Actress in a Play \u2013 ''[[Last of the Red Hot Lovers]]'' (Nominated)\n*1987 Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play \u2013 ''[[Broadway Bound]]'' ('''Won''')\n*1998 Best Performance by a Featured Actress in a Play \u2013 ''[[The Diary of Anne Frank (play)|The Diary of Anne Frank]]'' (Nominated)\n*2001 Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play \u2013 ''[[The Tale of the Allergist's Wife]]'' (Nominated)\n*2010 Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play \u2013 ''[[Collected Stories (play)|Collected Stories]]'' (Nominated)\n*2012 Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play \u2013 ''[[The Lyons]]'' (Nominated)\n\n'''Drama Desk Awards'''\n*1987 Outstanding Actress in a Play \u2013 ''Broadway Bound'' ('''Won''')\n*2008 Outstanding Featured Actress in a Play \u2013 ''The New Century'' ('''Won''')\n\n'''Obie Award'''\n*1994\u201395 Outstanding Actress \u2013 ''Death Defying Acts'' ('''Won''')\n*2012 Performance ''The Lyons'' ('''Won''')<ref>[http://lortel.org/Archives/Production/5299 ''The Lyons''] lortel.org, accessed December 31, 2015</ref>\n\n'''Golden Globe Awards'''\n*1979 Best TV Actress in a Musical or Comedy \u2013 ''[[Alice (TV series)|Alice]]'' ('''Won''')\n*1980 Best TV Actress in a Musical or Comedy \u2013 ''[[Alice (TV series)|Alice]]'' ('''Won''')\n*1981 Best TV Actress in a Musical or Comedy \u2013 ''[[Alice (TV series)|Alice]]'' (Nominated)\n\n'''Primetime Emmy Awards'''\n*1979 Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series \u2013 ''[[Alice (TV series)|Alice]]'' (Nominated)\n\n== Work ==\n\n=== Filmography ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1967\n|''Damn Yankees!''\n|Gloria Thorpe\n|\