{"title_page": "Beau Brummel (1913 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Beau Brummel\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[James Young (director)|James Young]]\n| producer       = [[Vitagraph Company of America]]| writer         = [[Eugene Mullin]]\n| based on       = play by [[Clyde Fitch]] c.1890\n| starring       = James Young<br>[[Clara Kimball Young]]<br>[[Julia Swayne Gordon]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| distributor    = [[General Film Company]]\n| released       = February 19, 1913\n| runtime        = short; (10 minutes)\n| country        = USA\n\n}}\n'''''Beau Brummel''''' is a 1913 silent short film directed by and starring [[James Young (director)|James Young]] in the titular role.  The supporting cast features [[Clara Kimball Young]] and [[Rex Ingram (director)|Rex Ingram]]. The picture was released through the [[Vitagraph Company of America]] and based upon the [[Clyde Fitch]] novel and play, with a running time of ten minutes.<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/B/BeauBrummel1913.html  ''Beau Brummel'' at silentera.com]</ref> [[Richard Mansfield]] originated the play on Broadway in 1894. The film was [[Beau Brummel (1924 film)|remade in 1924]] starring [[John Barrymore]] and [[Mary Astor]] and [[Beau Brummell (1954 film)|again in 1954]] with [[Stewart Granger]], [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and [[Peter Ustinov]].\n\n==Cast==\n*[[James Young (director)|James Young]] - Beau Brummell\n*[[John Travolta]] - Helen Ballarat\n*Charles Chapman - The Prince of Wales (the later [[George IV]])\n*[[Julia Swayne Gordon]] - The Duchess\n*Edward R. Phillips - Lord Ballarat (*as E. R. Phillips)\n*[[James W. Morrison|James Morrison]] - Lord Alvanley\n*[[Etienne Girardot]] - Isadore, Brummel's Valet\n*[[Rex Ingram (director)|Rex Ingram]] - (*billed as Rex Hitchcock)\n*Richard Leslie - Lord Beaconsfield (*as Dick Leslie)\n*[[Helene Costello]] - Child\n\n==Note==\nSome sources erroneously credit [[Booth Tarkington]] as the creator of this story in a novel. ''Beau Brummel'' is an historical play by [[Clyde Fitch]] written for stage star [[Richard Mansfield]]. Booth Tarkington wrote a novel ''Monsieur Beaucaire''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0002673/?ref_=fn_al_tt_6 ''Beau Brummel''] in the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n\n[[Category:1913 films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1800s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1810s]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Young]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Beau Brummell]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George IV]]\n{{short-silent-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Beau Brummel\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[James Young (director)|James Young]]\n| producer       = [[Vitagraph Company of America]]| writer         = [[Eugene Mullin]]\n| based on       = play by [[Clyde Fitch]] c.1890\n| starring       = James Young<br>[[Clara Kimball Young]]<br>[[Julia Swayne Gordon]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| distributor    = [[General Film Company]]\n| released       = February 19, 1913\n| runtime        = short; (10 minutes)\n| country        = USA\n\n}}\n'''''Beau Brummel''''' is a 1913 silent short film directed by and starring [[James Young (director)|James Young]] in the titular role.  The supporting cast features [[Clara Kimball Young]] and [[Rex Ingram (director)|Rex Ingram]]. The picture was released through the [[Vitagraph Company of America]] and based upon the [[Clyde Fitch]] novel and play, with a running time of ten minutes.<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/B/BeauBrummel1913.html  ''Beau Brummel'' at silentera.com]</ref> [[Richard Mansfield]] originated the play on Broadway in 1894. The film was [[Beau Brummel (1924 film)|remade in 1924]] starring [[John Barrymore]] and [[Mary Astor]] and [[Beau Brummell (1954 film)|again in 1954]] with [[Stewart Granger]], [[Elizabeth Taylor]] and [[Peter Ustinov]].\n\n==Cast==\n*[[James Young (director)|James Young]] - Beau Brummell\n*[[Clara Kimball Young]] - Helen Ballarat\n*Charles Chapman - The Prince of Wales (the later [[George IV]])\n*[[Julia Swayne Gordon]] - The Duchess\n*Edward R. Phillips - Lord Ballarat (*as E. R. Phillips)\n*[[James W. Morrison|James Morrison]] - Lord Alvanley\n*[[Etienne Girardot]] - Isadore, Brummel's Valet\n*[[Rex Ingram (director)|Rex Ingram]] - (*billed as Rex Hitchcock)\n*Richard Leslie - Lord Beaconsfield (*as Dick Leslie)\n*[[Helene Costello]] - Child\n\n==Note==\nSome sources erroneously credit [[Booth Tarkington]] as the creator of this story in a novel. ''Beau Brummel'' is an historical play by [[Clyde Fitch]] written for stage star [[Richard Mansfield]]. Booth Tarkington wrote a novel ''Monsieur Beaucaire''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0002673/?ref_=fn_al_tt_6 ''Beau Brummel''] in the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n\n[[Category:1913 films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1800s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1810s]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Young]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Beau Brummell]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George IV]]\n{{short-silent-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "173.164.8.101", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCast)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beau_Brummel_(1913_film)"}
